Dialogue: 0,0:00:00.94,0:00:07.55,Default,,0,0,0,,The most crucial moment in life is during decision making.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:08.90,0:00:14.01,Default,,0,0,0,,The Pacific War taught us the preciousness of peace.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:14.01,0:00:19.62,Default,,0,0,0,,But also instilled \Nnumerous lessons on how to live.{unsure, lit is "for the sake of living, precepts, numerous left behind"}
Dialogue: 0,0:00:24.14,0:00:31.39,Sign,,0,0,0,,{\fade(100,700)\c&H0007DF&\fs100\b1\bord0\blur1}Animentary\N{\b\c&HE0DBF3&}Decision
Dialogue: 0,0:00:35.16,0:00:43.33,Default,,0,0,30,,Wit is your weapon{honestly no clue what is megurase here, deepl says "rack one's brain"}\NRemember to use your head{智恵をめぐらせ 頭を使え}
Dialogue: 0,0:00:43.33,0:00:50.95,Default,,0,0,30,,Repress your anguish, \NIf you are a man{悩み抜け抜け 男なら}
Dialogue: 0,0:00:50.95,0:00:58.86,Default,,0,0,30,,One decision is enough \NTo make others cry or laugh{泣くも笑うも 決断ひとつ}
Dialogue: 0,0:00:58.86,0:01:06.69,Default,,0,0,30,,If you win, don't hold your head high, \NIf you lose, don't cry{勝っておごるな 敗れて泣くな}
Dialogue: 0,0:01:06.69,0:01:14.55,Default,,0,0,30,,Men, don't you ever let others see your tears{男 涙は見せぬもの}
Comment: 0,0:01:34.91,0:01:34.95,Default,,0,0,0,,{ch}
Dialogue: 0,0:01:49.23,0:01:54.78,Default,,0,0,0,,Having set the Pacific ablaze with a successful surprise attack on Hawaii, the Japanese army
Dialogue: 0,0:01:54.78,0:02:02.01,Default,,0,0,0,,capitalized on that momentum with advances on Hong Kong, the Malay Peninsula, the Philippines, Celebes, Borneo, and so on. {(with) great vigour (from the way splitting bamboo goes all down the stick); irresistible force​}
Dialogue: 0,0:02:02.01,0:02:05.47,Default,,0,0,0,,The stage was set for the capture of Java. {lit: encirclement; encircling net; tight besiegement was completed - he means Java was encircled/besieged/they finished setting up the trapping nets around it}
Dialogue: 1,0:02:06.33,0:02:11.71,Default,,0,0,0,,The ultimate goal of Operation Java \Nwas the acquisition of abundant oil resources.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:10.28,0:02:12.61,Sign,,0,0,0,,{\fade(150,100)\bord0\b1\fs60\c&HE2D2CF&\frz359.1\pos(828,102)}British Borneo
Dialogue: 0,0:02:10.28,0:02:12.61,Sign,,0,0,0,,{\fade(150,100)\bord0\b1\fs60\c&HE2D2CF&\frz0.2823\pos(574,688)}Dutch Borneo
Dialogue: 1,0:02:11.71,0:02:16.75,Default,,0,0,0,,As well as connecting the islands of Sumatra and Java \Ninto one big defensive ridge.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:17.22,0:02:21.09,Default,,0,0,0,,At that time, the island of Java \Nwas part of the Dutch East Indies. {not sure why he says "orando indoshina" (dutch indochina), would assume a slip of the tongue}
Dialogue: 2,0:02:21.09,0:02:23.51,Default,,0,0,0,,These days, we know it as Indonesia.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:21.41,0:02:24.92,Sign,,0,0,0,,{\fade(150,1400)\bord0\b1\fs25\c&HE3D2CE&\pos(885,454)\frz357.3\3c&H090606&}British Borneo
Dialogue: 0,0:02:21.41,0:02:24.92,Sign,,0,0,0,,{\fade(150,1400)\bord0\b1\fs25\c&HE3D2CE&\pos(807,657)\frz359.9\3c&H090606&}Dutch Borneo
Dialogue: 0,0:02:21.41,0:02:24.92,Sign,,0,0,0,,{\fade(150,1400)\bord1\b1\fs25\c&HE3D2CE&\frz16.97\pos(1113,104)\3c&H090606&}Philippines
Dialogue: 0,0:02:21.41,0:02:24.92,Sign,,0,0,0,,{\fade(150,1400)\bord0\b1\fs25\c&HE3D2CE&\3c&H090606&\pos(1211,838)\frz359.4}Celebes
Dialogue: 0,0:02:21.41,0:02:24.92,Sign,,0,0,0,,{\fade(150,1400)\bord0\b1\fs25\c&HE1DBE7&\3c&H090606&\pos(674,824)\frz358.7}Java
Dialogue: 0,0:02:21.41,0:02:24.92,Sign,,0,0,0,,{\fade(150,1400)\bord0\b1\fs25\c&HE3D2CE&\3c&H090606&\pos(202,480)\frz0.3342}Sumatra
Dialogue: 0,0:02:21.41,0:02:24.92,Sign,,0,0,0,,{\fade(150,1400)\bord0\b1\fs25\c&HE3D2CE&\3c&H090606&\frz24.22\pos(354,256)}Malaya
Dialogue: 0,0:02:21.41,0:02:24.92,Sign,,0,0,0,,{\fade(150,1400)\bord0\b1\fs25\c&HE3D2CE&\3c&H090606&\pos(482,34)\frz1.419}French Indochina
Dialogue: 0,0:02:25.72,0:02:30.71,Default,,0,0,0,,Firstly, the coveted oil fields and air bases \Nof Sumatra and Palembang were captured
Dialogue: 0,0:02:30.71,0:02:34.47,Default,,0,0,0,,by the combined forces of three Japanese \Nforward paratrooper battalions.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:35.50,0:02:42.72,Sign,,0,0,240,,{\fade(150,500)\b1\c&HEEE0E8&\bord0\blur1}Episode 9 \N {\fs150}The Fall of Java {ジャワ攻略}
Dialogue: 0,0:02:42.72,0:02:44.53,Default,,0,0,0,,From the General Staff's point of view,
Dialogue: 0,0:02:44.53,0:02:46.45,Default,,0,0,0,,among all Southern Strategy operations,
Dialogue: 0,0:02:46.45,0:02:50.03,Default,,0,0,0,,the capture of Java was likely to pose the biggest challenge.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:50.03,0:02:56.07,Default,,0,0,0,,The most pressing concern was the possible destruction of oil installations before the Japanese army takes over.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:48.10,0:03:50.89,Default,,0,0,0,,Through the efforts of 3 paratrooper regiments,
Dialogue: 0,0:03:50.89,0:03:54.00,Default,,0,0,0,,both the oil field and air base were captured intact.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:54.48,0:04:00.57,Default,,0,0,0,,Likewise, the Japanese army had previously conquered Sumatra, completing the isolation of Java. {siege; encirclement; envelopment; surrounding; besiegement}
Dialogue: 0,0:04:01.11,0:04:05.17,Default,,0,0,0,,Lieutenant General Imamura arrived in the area \Nwith his 40,000 strong 16th Army.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:05.17,0:04:10.03,Default,,0,0,0,,On February 27th, they began their march \Nthrough the island of Java.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:44.67,0:04:50.77,Default,,0,0,0,,The combined allied forces in Java were under the supreme command of Dutch Lieutenant General ter Poorten.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:51.40,0:04:57.71,Default,,0,0,0,,Defending Java were the combined ABDACOM forces: \NDutch, British, Americans, and Australians,
Dialogue: 0,0:04:57.71,0:04:59.34,Default,,0,0,0,,as well as local conscripts.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:59.34,0:05:00.78,Default,,0,0,0,,A joint force of 80,000.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:00.78,0:05:03.62,Default,,0,0,0,,Meaning they outnumbered the Japanese 2 to 1.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:04.27,0:05:07.09,Default,,0,0,0,,However, the combined Dutch command
Dialogue: 0,0:05:07.09,0:05:12.10,Default,,0,0,0,,was facing the risk of an uprising of 50 million dissidents \Nsuddenly taking up arms against them. {was "could convert as many as 50 million local civilians into soldiers." in HA but he's wrong}
Dialogue: 0,0:05:13.56,0:05:18.91,Default,,0,0,0,,By that time, in Indonesia, \Nunder the joint leadership of Sukarno and Hatta,
Dialogue: 0,0:05:18.91,0:05:25.07,Default,,0,0,0,,the National Independence Movement, \Nresisting Dutch rule, was thriving. {prosperous; flourishing; thriving; successful}
Dialogue: 0,0:05:27.45,0:05:32.45,Default,,0,0,0,,Anticipating the Japanese army's approach, \NRear Admiral Doorman of the Dutch Navy
Dialogue: 0,0:05:32.45,0:05:35.35,Default,,0,0,0,,ordered the combined allied fleet to set sail.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:35.35,0:05:41.70,Default,,0,0,0,,But it was destroyed effortlessly by the Japanese fleet \Nduring the Battle for Surabaya, off the coast of Batavia.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:09.16,0:06:15.20,Default,,0,0,0,,However, among the ships then anchored at Bantam Bay \Nwatching this battle unfold with bated breath,
Dialogue: 0,0:06:15.20,0:06:19.53,Default,,0,0,0,,four Japanese transport vessels \Nwere hit by torpedoes.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:20.38,0:06:28.03,Default,,0,0,0,,Ironically enough, those friendly torpedoes passed right under \Nan already foundering American cruiser.  {added}
Dialogue: 0,0:06:31.39,0:06:36.40,Default,,0,0,0,,Among the hit vessels was Sakuramaru, carrying Lieutenant General Imamura, the 16th Army commander. {it was actually ryuujomaru that we've seen before irl, but I guess we'd better stick to the text}
Dialogue: 0,0:06:36.40,0:06:42.69,Default,,0,0,0,,To his sheer surprise, Lieutenant General Imamura, \Nfound himself swimming through the warm southern waters. {lit is something like "had one scene of swimming"}
Dialogue: 0,0:07:03.45,0:07:09.12,Default,,0,0,0,,However, Lieutenant General Imamura \Ncasually switched ships, and on March 1st, {no clue what's this taizen; has to be "with calm; composed; self-possessed; firm" tho seems a bit off}
Dialogue: 0,0:07:09.12,0:07:13.91,Default,,0,0,0,,the Japanese army launched a full-scale landing \Non the island of Java with all available forces.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:45.75,0:07:51.09,Default,,0,0,0,,The main body of the 16th Army was split \Ninto three formations, each one making steady progress.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:51.09,0:07:53.74,Default,,0,0,0,,With Bandung as their goal, all three were advancing.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:58.62,0:08:01.04,Default,,0,0,0,,All forces have successfully made it ashore!
Dialogue: 0,0:08:01.60,0:08:03.03,Default,,0,0,0,,What is the battle situation?
Dialogue: 0,0:08:03.63,0:08:07.55,Default,,0,0,0,,It looks exceedingly favorable for us. \NYou could even say too much so.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:07.55,0:08:08.61,Default,,0,0,0,,I see.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:08.61,0:08:12.98,Default,,0,0,0,,Both sides are conserving themselves \Nright until the battle's conclusion.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:12.98,0:08:13.63,Default,,0,0,0,,Roger.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:14.06,0:08:19.08,Default,,0,0,0,,We don't fight to kill as many as we can, but to force \Na surrender with minimal casualties on our side.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:24.98,0:08:27.69,Default,,0,0,0,,Relax, it's still a long way off. {matter for the future; something that is a long way off; something that is not going to happen anytime soon}
Dialogue: 0,0:08:41.99,0:08:47.55,Default,,0,0,0,,Unaware of the Japanese army's calculation, the combined forces commander ter Poorten was worried sick.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:48.13,0:08:51.29,Default,,0,0,0,,We're reviewing combat reports \Nfrom each of the districts.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:51.29,0:08:53.64,Default,,0,0,0,,The Japanese forces number 30,000 to 40,000.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:55.39,0:08:57.62,Default,,0,0,0,,Can't we get reliable information sooner?
Dialogue: 0,0:08:57.62,0:09:02.31,Default,,0,0,0,,As usual with coalitions, it always takes some strong time to relay information.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:02.31,0:09:05.91,Default,,0,0,0,,Exactitude! Exactitude is what we need!
Dialogue: 0,0:09:10.29,0:09:12.28,Default,,0,0,0,,What about the local populace?
Dialogue: 0,0:09:12.28,0:09:15.76,Default,,0,0,0,,Why not employ them \Nfor obtaining reliable information?
Dialogue: 0,0:09:15.76,0:09:18.20,Default,,0,0,0,,Yes. Well, as a matter of fact...
Dialogue: 0,0:09:18.20,0:09:19.32,Default,,0,0,0,,What is it ?
Dialogue: 0,0:09:44.04,0:09:47.57,Default,,0,0,0,,Landed in the Kragan Cape area - \Naround 50,000 Japanese.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:48.54,0:09:49.40,Default,,0,0,0,,50,000?
Dialogue: 0,0:09:50.03,0:09:53.53,Default,,0,0,0,,And apparently, 80,000 more Japanese \Nare landing in Bantam Bay.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:54.30,0:09:55.45,Default,,0,0,0,,80,000?
Dialogue: 0,0:10:00.53,0:10:02.99,Default,,0,0,0,,What? 200,000?
Dialogue: 0,0:10:02.99,0:10:05.43,Default,,0,0,0,,Putting together various reports from the locals,
Dialogue: 0,0:10:05.43,0:10:08.52,Default,,0,0,0,,they established that \Nthe Japanese numbered 200,000 in total.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:12.05,0:10:16.60,Default,,0,0,0,,These estimates \Nwere grossly inflated by the natives
Dialogue: 0,0:10:16.60,0:10:19.95,Default,,0,0,0,,and in this fashion passed on to the Dutch.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:20.41,0:10:26.36,Default,,0,0,0,,It was believed until the very end \Nthat the 16th Army numbered up to 200,000 troops.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:27.69,0:10:32.34,Default,,0,0,0,,The Dutch efforts at gathering intelligence \Nwere not only curtailed by the natives,
Dialogue: 0,0:10:32.34,0:10:34.92,Default,,0,0,0,,but also by their own lackluster methods. {REALLY unsure about this sentence, believing DeepL's "The Dutch Allies were not only misled by the locals' information, but also by their intelligence-gathering efforts."}
Dialogue: 0,0:10:36.94,0:10:40.80,Default,,0,0,0,,The Natives from the National \NIndependence Movement made every effort
Dialogue: 0,0:10:40.80,0:10:45.29,Default,,0,0,0,,to expedite the Japanese army's advance \Nand ensure a success for the operation. {lit: in all aspects, led/guided the japanese army to profit/advantage}
Dialogue: 0,0:11:04.53,0:11:07.78,Default,,0,0,0,,Any new intel on Japanese activity? \NWe need to know.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:07.78,0:11:10.50,Default,,0,0,0,,What? \NYou want to know about Japanese activity?
Dialogue: 0,0:11:10.50,0:11:13.75,Default,,0,0,0,,Good luck with that. \NThe newspaper has yet to hit our desk.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:45.03,0:11:49.97,Default,,0,0,0,,On the frontline, the enemy is not putting up \Nmuch of a fight. It's a bit anticlimactic, even.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:49.97,0:11:53.94,Default,,0,0,0,,The less resistance we meet, \Nthe less casualties we take.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:11.73,0:12:13.59,Default,,0,0,0,,A new tank model?
Dialogue: 0,0:12:15.48,0:12:21.75,Default,,0,0,0,,So, as of March 3rd, we have received a report \Nthat no Japanese troops have yet landed on Java proper. {/island of ...}
Dialogue: 0,0:12:21.75,0:12:23.49,Default,,0,0,0,,Eh? What a load of bull! {sounds a bit too vernacular for HA, did you write this Paul?}
Dialogue: 0,0:12:40.26,0:12:41.88,Default,,0,0,0,,It's a Japanese tank!
Dialogue: 0,0:12:55.25,0:13:00.22,Default,,0,0,0,,In order to break the morale of the Dutch forces, \NLieutenant General Imamura
Dialogue: 0,0:13:00.22,0:13:02.58,Default,,0,0,0,,launched a massive deception campaign. {/propaganda broadcast}
Dialogue: 0,0:13:05.85,0:13:09.98,Default,,0,0,0,,The Japanese army in Burma \Nseems to have entered Rangoon unopposed. {added cause I like this word}
Dialogue: 0,0:13:10.85,0:13:11.91,Default,,0,0,0,,No way!
Dialogue: 0,0:13:11.91,0:13:13.55,Default,,0,0,0,,Did he just say Rangoon? {a bit unsure about this part}
Dialogue: 0,0:13:14.08,0:13:17.96,Default,,0,0,0,,In Britain, Churchill's cabinet \Nhas assumed responsibility for the fall of Singapore.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:17.96,0:13:20.28,Default,,0,0,0,,It appears that they will resign in full. {mass resignation}
Dialogue: 0,0:13:22.99,0:13:26.05,Default,,0,0,0,,The natives found the broadcast \Nabsolutely delightful. {/campaign }
Dialogue: 0,0:13:26.05,0:13:30.76,Default,,0,0,0,,The Japanese troops have furthermore solidified the natives' support for their campaign. {/were advancing while receiving even more guidance from ...}
Dialogue: 0,0:14:26.78,0:14:30.30,Default,,0,0,0,,However, as they were approaching Bandung,
Dialogue: 0,0:14:30.30,0:14:33.58,Default,,0,0,0,,the resistance of the combined Dutch forces \Nincreased drastically.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:26.34,0:15:33.12,Default,,0,0,0,,It was at this point in time, when the Japanese army's steady advance seemingly ground to a standstill. {he adds "on the front line" for some reason}
Dialogue: 0,0:15:33.69,0:15:35.35,Default,,0,0,0,,On March 7th,
Dialogue: 0,0:15:35.35,0:15:40.02,Default,,0,0,0,,a suicide corps was formed \Nwith more than 700 Japanese soldiers.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:40.02,0:15:42.66,Default,,0,0,0,,They were to infiltrate the suburbs of Bandung. {lit: it was decided that they rush into the ...}
Dialogue: 0,0:15:45.15,0:15:51.20,Default,,0,0,0,,With those begrudging Indonesians, \Neven guerrilla warfare seems like a pipe dream. {HA was "then guerrilla warfare is almost inevitable." but I think my variant is correct - mind you this is dutch speaking}
Dialogue: 0,0:15:51.60,0:15:54.17,Default,,0,0,0,,Even if I order my Dutch troops to surrender,
Dialogue: 0,0:15:54.17,0:15:59.31,Default,,0,0,0,,the troops of other nations are free to disregard \Na ceasefire order from me, if they so desire. {I hope he means this by "may ignore my ceasefire order" and not "I don't want them to ignore ..."}
Dialogue: 0,0:16:03.65,0:16:04.71,Default,,0,0,0,,Commander.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:04.71,0:16:07.95,Default,,0,0,0,,As long as our fellow Dutchmen stand tall and fight,
Dialogue: 0,0:16:07.95,0:16:10.67,Default,,0,0,0,,fellow British and Australian soldiers \Nwon't back down.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:13.76,0:16:18.05,Default,,0,0,0,,Although the words of Major General Sitwell, \NCommander-in-Chief of British-Australian forces
Dialogue: 0,0:16:18.05,0:16:22.06,Default,,0,0,0,,channeled determination, \Nhe was out of touch with the brutal reality. {vain; fruitless; futile; ineffective}
Dialogue: 0,0:17:03.52,0:17:07.85,Default,,0,0,0,,Major General Pesman, tasked with the defense \Nof the Northern-Central district of Bandung,
Dialogue: 0,0:17:07.85,0:17:13.86,Default,,0,0,0,,surrendered willingly in just under few hours \Nafter the Japanese suicide corps' attack had started.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:14.39,0:17:18.24,Default,,0,0,0,,Have you checked it's a herald from Pesman, \Nfrom the Northern-Central district of Bandung? {/messenger} {/of Major General }
Dialogue: 0,0:17:18.24,0:17:20.89,Default,,0,0,0,,Yes. Without a doubt, he is a truce bearer.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:21.87,0:17:24.75,Default,,0,0,0,,{Strange,/}All that, despite the determined resistance \Nthey've been mounting...
Dialogue: 0,0:17:36.43,0:17:38.76,Default,,0,0,0,,I believe, the enemy is setting a trap for us.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:38.76,0:17:41.74,Default,,0,0,0,,Consequently, \Nwe may have to level the city.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:41.74,0:17:43.46,Default,,0,0,0,,We have no choice but to set it on fire. {not sure what he means or why is it so: setting on fire; setting afire cannot be helped; unavoidable}
Dialogue: 0,0:17:47.75,0:17:48.76,Default,,0,0,0,,Sir.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:50.48,0:17:54.05,Default,,0,0,0,,I understand what you're getting at. \NThe casualties on our side are mounting.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:54.51,0:17:57.84,Default,,0,0,0,,The enemy will continue to resist \Nand won't come out of the city, {I hope he means this, also implying [if we fall for that trap/believe their surrender]}
Dialogue: 0,0:17:57.84,0:18:00.60,Default,,0,0,0,,probably preparing a fortified position \Nfor a decisive showdown.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:00.60,0:18:03.85,Default,,0,0,0,,However, that would entail \Nmassive collateral damage on the locals. {/a lot of natives would have to be sacrificed} {this may sound weird from a gapanese general, but historically, Imamura really was exceptionally lenient and merciful towards locals and even was spared an the trials}
Dialogue: 0,0:18:03.85,0:18:06.30,Default,,0,0,0,,No, we will evacuate as many as we can.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:09.11,0:18:11.17,Default,,0,0,0,,Sir, please make a decision.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:11.71,0:18:13.61,Default,,0,0,0,,Time is running out.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:14.21,0:18:18.28,Default,,0,0,0,,Even if it increases the strain on our own forces, \Nthe local populace must be protected.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:18.28,0:18:19.93,Default,,0,0,0,,Burning the city is unacceptable.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:19.93,0:18:24.47,Default,,0,0,0,,By inflicting such a suffering on them here, \Nwe'll alienate them for the rest of the occupation. {cooperation; collaboration; help; support}
Dialogue: 0,0:18:24.47,0:18:27.13,Default,,0,0,0,,We didn't come here to make the locals suffer.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:28.49,0:18:29.20,Default,,0,0,0,,Roger!
Dialogue: 0,0:18:30.50,0:18:33.42,Default,,0,0,0,,Okay, let's rope the secret service agency in.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:34.21,0:18:39.22,Default,,0,0,0,,With an interpreter to escort him, a Japanese military officer disguised himself as a civilian.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:39.22,0:18:44.26,Default,,0,0,0,,As a part of a big ploy, he had already infiltrated Bandung and was awaiting for an opportunity.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:44.79,0:18:49.27,Default,,0,0,0,,On March 7th, before the Japanese troops \Noverwhelmed Lembang, {rushed into }
Dialogue: 0,0:18:49.27,0:18:52.90,Default,,0,0,0,,upon getting the order \Nfrom his military commander, he enacted the plan. {actually "departed/set out" but I think he means "started acting"}
Dialogue: 0,0:18:58.45,0:19:00.64,Default,,0,0,0,,First Lieutenant of the Japanese Army Yanagawa. {the info on him is very scarce, but if my findings are true, it's Munenari Yanagawa, army intelligence officer with a really fascinating bio; I couldn't find any mentions of him coming to negotiations with the dutch, though}
Dialogue: 0,0:19:00.64,0:19:05.42,Default,,0,0,0,,I'd like an audience with the Supreme Commander \Nof the Allied Forces on Java, Lieutenant General ter Poorten.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:06.77,0:19:07.92,Default,,0,0,0,,{NO HA LINE HERE} {because none is needed ¯\_(ツ)_/¯}
Dialogue: 0,0:19:11.07,0:19:11.86,Default,,0,0,0,,What?!
Dialogue: 0,0:19:31.32,0:19:34.68,Default,,0,0,0,,The Japanese army had taken the Island of Java \Ncompletely under control.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:34.68,0:19:36.50,Default,,0,0,0,,Stifling Bandung as well. {siege; encirclement; envelopment; surrounding; besiegement}
Dialogue: 0,0:19:36.50,0:19:41.96,Default,,0,0,0,,I suggest that you surrender immediately. \NProlonging resistance any further is futile.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:07.65,0:21:12.78,Default,,0,0,0,,On March 8th, the Dutch combined forces \Nfinally laid down their arms.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:13.23,0:21:16.71,Default,,0,0,0,,The Bandung District Defense Commander \NMajor General Pesman,
Dialogue: 0,0:21:16.71,0:21:20.21,Default,,0,0,0,,Governor-General Tjarda, \Nand Lieutenant General ter Poorten,
Dialogue: 0,0:21:20.21,0:21:23.67,Default,,0,0,0,,as well as the Army Chief of Staff \NMajor General Bakkers - 4 men in total {really unsure why he says "pakkasu no 4 mei" - maybe it's really something like "four pakkas' representatives" or w/e} {https://www.tracesofwar.nl/persons/103550/Bakkers-Rudolph.htm - courtesy of @DefraggedHistory}
Dialogue: 0,0:21:23.67,0:21:27.64,Default,,0,0,0,,came to Kalijati \Nto meet with the Commander-in-Chief Imamura.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:28.91,0:21:31.99,Default,,0,0,0,,The scene of destruction in the Bandung area \Npresents a sorry sight. {/disastrous scene; terrible spectacle around bandung is too terrible to look at; unbearable to look at}
Dialogue: 0,0:21:33.05,0:21:35.82,Default,,0,0,0,,It is needless to subject the locals \Nto more misery.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:37.78,0:21:41.30,Default,,0,0,0,,I wish to surrender Bandung on good terms.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:41.85,0:21:44.47,Default,,0,0,0,,The surrender of Bandung is besides the point!
Dialogue: 0,0:21:44.47,0:21:48.79,Default,,0,0,0,,What the Japanese military demands \Nis a complete, unconditional surrender.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:16.09,0:22:21.86,Default,,0,0,0,,The Bandung Radio Station \Nfinally broadcast a ceasefire order to all forces.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:25.43,0:22:30.76,Default,,0,0,0,,Thus, the capture of Java, which was expected to pose \Nthe biggest challenge of the entire Southern Strategy,
Dialogue: 0,0:22:30.76,0:22:34.56,Default,,0,0,0,,thanks to discretion in planning \Nand the cooperation of the natives
Dialogue: 0,0:22:34.56,0:22:38.34,Default,,0,0,0,,unexpectedly ended in a complete success, \Nachieved with limited casualties.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:59.03,0:23:05.99,Default,,0,0,0,,On March 10th, commanded by Lieutenant General Imamura, \Nthe 16th Army triumphantly entered Bandung.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:29.25,0:23:36.01,Default,,0,0,0,,In the entirety of the Pacific War, no other operation was so warmly welcomed by the natives as Operation Java.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:36.01,0:23:41.21,Default,,0,0,0,,This and the fact it met all the objectives according to plan, \Nmade it truly a one-of-a-kind operation. {/it's said it was the only ... to be ...}
Dialogue: 0,0:23:42.67,0:23:46.13,Default,,0,0,0,,Some say, the overarching decisions \Nof Lieutenant General Imamura,
Dialogue: 0,0:23:46.13,0:23:48.91,Default,,0,0,0,,in considering the natives' interests all along,
Dialogue: 0,0:23:48.91,0:23:55.22,Default,,0,0,0,,by not resorting to the tactics of complete annihilation, {actually "rejected tactics of setting on fire; setting afire" but i couldn't wrap this around in english} \Nhighlighted his humanity. {actually "love" but I think he means "love for people" so humanity it is}
Dialogue: 0,0:23:58.39,0:24:07.92,Sign,,0,0,0,,{\fade(100,0)}The Pacific War taught us the preciousness of peace.\NBut also instilled numerous lessons on how to live.{太平洋戦争はわれわれに平和の尊さを教えたがまた生きるための教訓を数多くのこしている}
Dialogue: 0,0:24:09.47,0:24:12.79,Default,,0,0,0,,One of the Southern Strategy operations \Nwas the capture of the Celebes.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:12.79,0:24:15.55,Default,,0,0,0,,This time as well, the paratroopers were its vanguard. {I think it's an idiom for "to start/arrive first on scene"}
Dialogue: 0,0:24:15.55,0:24:18.72,Default,,0,0,0,,Although a cooperation \Nwith the ground troops was promoted,{honestly, I don't understand the meaning of what he says so winding it because jikai}
Dialogue: 0,0:24:18.72,0:24:22.27,Default,,0,0,0,,the proud Skyborne Soldiers, \Nthe paratroopers
Dialogue: 0,0:24:22.27,0:24:26.90,Default,,0,0,0,,were mostly disdainful of ground troops, giving gradual rise to animosity.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:27.21,0:24:32.26,Default,,0,0,0,,But at a later point, this would spark\Ninto a brazen decision, causing a major blunder.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:32.72,0:24:33.55,Default,,0,0,0,,The next decision:
Dialogue: 0,0:24:33.55,0:24:36.58,Default,,0,0,0,,The Navy Paratrooper Corps. Please look forward to it.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:33.55,0:24:38.50,Sign,,0,0,0,,Episode 10 \NThe Navy Paratrooper Corps {海軍落下傘部隊}
Comment: 0,0:24:43.11,0:24:43.15,Default,,0,0,0,,{ch}
Dialogue: 0,0:24:44.00,0:24:48.66,Default,,0,0,50,,If you're a man, let's put your strength to test{男だったら　力を試せ}
Dialogue: 0,0:24:48.66,0:24:53.00,Default,,0,0,50,,If you are a man, keep your hopes sizzling{男だったら　希望(のぞみ)を燃やせ}
Dialogue: 0,0:24:53.00,0:24:57.36,Default,,0,0,50,,If you are a man, don't lose your heart{男だったら　くじけるな}
Dialogue: 0,0:24:57.36,0:25:05.93,Default,,0,0,50,,Because there's just you and me, a man and a man{俺もおまえも　男と男}
Dialogue: 0,0:25:05.93,0:25:14.36,Default,,0,0,50,,With crimson blood flowing in our veins all the same{おなじ真赤な　血が通う}
